makeFilteredFutuDBSqlQuery

public static java.sql.PreparedStatement makeFilteredFutuDBSqlQuery(java.sql.Connection connection,
                                                                    java.lang.String sqlQuery,
                                                                    java.lang.String deviceName,
                                                                    java.lang.String loggerApplicationName,
                                                                    java.lang.String startTimeName,
                                                                    java.lang.String startTime,
                                                                    java.lang.String endTimeName,
                                                                    java.lang.String endTime)
                                                             throws java.sql.SQLException
Create a valid common WHERE clause using the supplied conditions for any routine_db query (also protect against SQL injection)

Empty or null search parameters are ignored. Timestamp formats: PostgreSQL 2012-09-06 13:13:30.913+03 and ISO 8601 2012-09-06T13:13:30.913+03. Verify strings before insertion to avoid SQL injection attacks. Timestamps are protected with timestamp casts. All strings are inserted with preparedStatement.setString() methods.

Note that you cannot use aliases for tables devices and logger_applications in sqlQuery as they would mask the search conditions on devices.device_name and logger_applications.logger_application_name. In addition, devices and logger_applications tables must always be included in the list of tables after FROM. Always add ", devices , logger_applications " to the last entries after FROM if those tables are not already included into the query, because makeFilteredFutuDBSqlQuery() needs those tables for handling possible device_name and logger_application_name query parameters.

Alternatively, you can set device_name and/or logger_application_name to null if it would not affect the query result (e.g. requesting mccs data). NOTE: having devices or logger_applications after FROM while there is no corresponding condition on devices.device_name or logger_applications.logger_application_name, causes unpredictable joins that may repeat result lines! So make query parameter null in the caller's code if the parameter does not have real use in the query.

Parameters:
connection - The PostgreSQL 9.0/9.1 routine database connection.
sqlQuery - The base SQL query that needs additional query restrictions.
deviceName - Limit results of the search only devices belonging to this user (only returns the same instance). Null or empty give all.
loggerApplicationName - Limit results of the search only to logging context of the device/user. Null or empty give all.
startTimeName - Name of the DB column against which the start time is compared in SQL. Can be the same as endTimeName.
startTime - PostgreSQL/ISO8601 timestamp to limit returned devices to those added at the same or newer time than the given time.
endTimeName - Name of the DB column against which the end time is compared in SQL. Can be the same as startTimeName.
endTime - PostgreSQL/ISO8601 timestamp to limit returned devices to those added at the same or newer time than the given time.
Returns:
The prepared SQL statement object created from the supplied SQL string concatenated with "WHERE ..." if any of the filter parameters is not empty and the connection is not null. Null is returned if problems arose.
Throws:
java.sql.SQLException - Indicates problems in the database query. By throwing this up, we can issue a proper HTTP 500 "Internal server error" message.

addWHEREorAND

private static java.lang.String addWHEREorAND(boolean first)
Create clause join operators for filter clauses in an SQL request (for the makeFilteredFutuDBSqlQuery() method)

Parameters:
first - true returns "WHERE" and false "AND", with suitable whitespace padding
Returns:
"\\nWHERE " or "\\nAND ".
